---
description: Reduce common LLM coding mistakes — think first, simplify, surgical edits, verify goals
globs:
alwaysApply: true
---

## When

- Implementing or reviewing code changes in any project.
- The task could be over-scoped, over-abstracted, or drift from the user's request.

## Do

- State assumptions explicitly; ask when uncertain instead of guessing silently.
- Prefer the minimum code that solves the problem; skip speculative features and abstractions.
- Touch only what the request requires; match existing style in surrounding code.
- Turn tasks into verifiable success criteria and check them before handing work back.
- Remove imports/variables/functions **your** changes made unused.

## Don’t

- Refactor or “improve” unrelated code, comments, or formatting.
- Add error handling for impossible scenarios or flexibility that was not requested.
- Delete pre-existing dead code unless the user asked.
- Approve or ship when a simpler approach was obvious and skipped.

**Working if:** diffs stay focused, fewer rewrites from overcomplication, and clarifying questions come before implementation.
